  "texts": [
    "Beyond a conventional assessment setting, AI-driven data analytics tools can also help educators and administrators gather insights into student performance, identify trends, predict future academic outcomes, and recommend interventions to support struggling students.",
    "the accuracy, fairness, and security of the test content.",
    "For instance, adaptive testing programs, such as the Graduate Record Examinations and the National Council Licensure Examination, maintain extensive item banks, ensuring that each examinee receives a unique set of questions tailored to their ability level.In response to this growing demand, automatic item generation (AIG) was proposed over a decade ago by educational measurement researchers as a cost-effective solution to generate a large number of high-quality items (e.g., Gierl & Haladyna, 2012; Holling et al., 2009; Lai et al., 2009).",
    "One traditional approach of AIG was to use computer algorithms to generate items based on cognitive models (representing the underlying cognitive processes that items are designed to measure) and item models (structured item templates) developed by subject matter experts.",
    "These automatically generated items are then evaluated by human experts (Gierl & Lai, 2012)."
  ]
}